  "response": "The relevant finding is `crime_00025` (\"Icon-Sized Raster\") on `src/assets/check-icon.png`. Quoting its dimensions verbatim:\n\n> \"dimensions: 32 × 32 px (≤ 64 threshold both sides)\"\n> \"format: png\"\n\nAt 32×32, a PNG locks the indicator to one resolution: it renders crisply at 1× CSS pixels, but on the 2× and 3× displays most users actually have (Retina laptops, modern phones), the browser upscales those 32 fixed pixels and the icon goes soft. Status indicators tend to also get used at multiple sizes (inline with text, in a toolbar, in a larger empty-state) — each new size either ships another PNG variant (`@2x`, `@3x`, a 48px copy) or accepts visible blur. An SVG sidesteps both problems: one file renders sharply at every DPI and every size, and for a simple shape like a check or status dot it ships fewer bytes than even a single 32×32 PNG, let alone a `@2x`/`@3x` set. It's also restyleable via CSS (`currentColor`, `fill`), so the same asset can serve success/warning/error states without duplicating the file.",
